{
  "text": "Categorizing and analyzing stress measures within these underlying constructs (e.g. threat of physical harm) instead of by life domain (e.g. work stress, relationship strain) may improve predictive models. For example, [CITATION_1] classified traumatic events intoself-and otheroriented events (e.g. being personally abused versus death of child), and then examined how these two types of events were differentially associated with loneliness in a subset of older adults from the HRS. As an example for future work, items that capture whether someone felt that they were physically in danger at different points across their lifespan could be selected from a variety of stress measures such as a traumatic life events scale that asks about witnessing violence or being deployed in the military, a neighborhood measure that asks about sense of safety in the community, and a childhood adverse events measure that captures whether they were being physically abused in childhood. A composite of these 'threat of physical harm' items could then be created and tested.",
